{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01433N16oWghgbesCWibkSTm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The formula written to M2 is:\n\n```\n=SUMPRODUCT((MOD(COLUMN(P1:X1),2)=0)*(O2:W535=$A2)*(P2:X535))\n```\n\n**Result: 9,480** (1,920 + 1,920 + 600 + 5,040 from 4 matches)\n\n### How it works, broken down:\n\nThe data from column O onward alternates: **part number, quantity, part number, quantity, ...** So odd columns (O, Q, S, U, W) hold part numbers and even columns (P, R, T, V, X) hold quantities.\n\nThe formula uses three arrays multiplied together inside SUMPRODUCT:\n\n1. **`(MOD(COLUMN(P1:X1),2)=0)`** — A filter that returns 1 for even-numbered columns (P, R, T, V, X) and 0 for odd ones. This ensures we only look at positions where O:W contains a part number and P:X contains the matching quantity.\n\n2. **`(O2:W535=$A2)`** — Checks every cell in the part-number range against your raw part number in A2. Returns 1 where it matches, 0 where it doesn't.\n\n3. **`(P2:X535)`** — The quantity values, shifted one column right from the part numbers.\n\nSUMPRODUCT multiplies these three arrays element-by-element and sums everything. Only cells where **all three** conditions are non-zero contribute: the column must be a quantity column (filter #1), the adjacent part number must match A2 (filter #2), and the value summed is the quantity itself (filter #3).\n\n### The big picture for your sheet:\n\n- **L2** = `SUM(B2:K2)` — total raw parts shipping to other facilities\n- **M2** = total raw parts needed to build completed parts here\n- **L2 + M2** = total raw parts needed overall (shipping + building)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4211,"cache_read_input_tokens":16848,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4211},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":nul